        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName>Birmingham</placeName>
                    <date>Jan 16 1877</date>
                    <salute>My Dear Sir,</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>If our views on Evolution are sound it seems to me that they must include many explanations of the diseased processes of man. I am writing a book on Diseases of Women, &amp; am trying to borrow light from the “Descent of Man”   I send two or three proof sheets containing a sample &amp; though I know how you hesitate to express an opinion on a matter out of the line of your experience, if you can see your way to criticise (in general terms) my views I should like to know your opinion.<ref target="#foot.f1"/></p>
<p>I have another matter in which I think I have done better than in the present case, hermaphroditism, which I should like to submit to you in a few days.<ref target="#foot.f2"/></p>
<p>“Cross Fertilisation” is splendid. I have just finished a review for Spectator.<ref target="#foot.f3"/></p>
<p>Yours truly, | Lawson Tait</p> 
                </div>
            </div>

            
            
            
        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">No proof-sheets from Tait’s book <hi rend="italic">Diseases of women</hi> (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_10061.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">L. Tait 1877</ref>) have been found in the Darwin Archive–CUL. Tait claimed that CD’s theory of the descent of humans from other animals had shown that sexual instincts were the most necessary and prevalent of all instincts evolved by the necessities of animal existence (<hi rend="italic">ibid.</hi>, pp. 48–9).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">In <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_10061.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">L. Tait 1877</ref>, p. 200, Tait argued that the incidence of hermaphroditism in humans could be explained by CD’s theory of descent and regarded as reversion.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">Tait’s review of <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_8595.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Cross and self fertilisation</hi></ref> appeared in the <hi rend="italic">Spectator</hi>, 10 February 1877, p. 17.</note>
        </div>        
            
